<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-902-162  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 902 162.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Nov 15 1989 n1485 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Stateside. (corporate users seek microcomputer industry standards)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Thomas, Matthew.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Large US corporations are forming user groups that try toinfluence the development and standardization of microcomputertechnologies.andP;  Fifty-four corporations have signed up with the 486Standardization Committee, which has asked developers ofhigh-capacity floppy disk drives to send sample drives forevaluation by the committee's technical staff.andP;  The committeewould then recommend which drives microcomputer manufacturersshould use to maintain industry standards.andP;  Electronic firms areconcerned that the 486 Standardization Committee will be able toinfluence purchasing patterns of other large corporations.andP;  Theexistence of the committee points up the need for standards in themicrocomputer industry.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United StatesUser GroupsCompaniesMicrocomputersStandardization486 Standardization CommitteeGoals and Objectives.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>